f=Executive Office/vista/marketplace/north-star-metric/references/red-flags.md · h1:Red Flags: North Star Metric=Common ways skill's output goes wrong concrete examples, they're bad, fix them. · h:to use this document=Scan NSM spec `metric_tree_builder.py` output before publishing team board. red flag shows *bad* version next *good* version, anchored Sean Ellis's NSM framing, Amplitude's archetype model, OMTM (Lean Analytics). · h2:Red Flag Missing counter-metrics=**Symptom.** NSM spec input metrics, which team trying drive up. anti-metrics, counter-metrics. **Why it's bad.** NSM powerful lever gamed. Without counter-metrics, team hit NSM number through harmful means bad signups, junk content, low-quality usage. number goes up; business goes down. **Bad example:** "NSM: Messages sent WAU. Inputs: WAU. Messages session. Sessions week. (No anti-metrics. counter-metrics.) months later: messages WAU doubled; abuse reports 9x; revenue impression down 35% due spam-driven engagement.)" **Good example:** "NSM: Messages sent WAU. Inputs: WAU, Messages/session, Sessions/week. Anti-metrics (must degrade): Messages reported spam (threshold: stay below 0.4%). Abuse reports 10k messages (threshold: stay below 12). Blocked-user rate (threshold: stay below monthly). Counter-metrics (the business protection): Revenue message (threshold: stay above $0.018; NSM goes while revenue/msg goes down, losing bad messages). NSM ships anti counter." **How catch it.** Read NSM spec. Search "anti" "counter". either missing, guardrails absent. · h2:Red Flag Leading indicators lagging indicators=**Symptom.** Team labels "weekly retention" leading indicator. Weekly retention measured day **Why it's bad.** leading indicator move *before* input metric. gives early-warning signal. Weekly retention measured days later; then, input already moved not. team reading speedometer, road ahead. **Bad example:** "Input: weekly retention. Leading indicator: weekly retention. (Tautology.)" **Good example:** "Input: weekly retention (measured day 7). Leading indicators (move days/weeks earlier): Day-1 session count new signups (predicts whether they retain day 7). First-action-completion session (predicts day-1 return). Re-engagement notification CTR (predicts session required week-1 retention). move 1-6 days before retention measured." **How catch it.** leading indicator, ask: "how many days/weeks before input move?" days 'same time', it's leading. · h2:Red Flag NSM exposes strategic disagreement (and team tries fix metric)=**Symptom.** Five candidate NSMs. Team can't pick. Three weeks debate. **Why it's bad.** NSM debate often proxy strategy debate. team can't agree NSM, they don't agree what business they're in. NSM downstream strategy; trying fix without fixing strategy debate theater. **Bad example:** "NSM candidates after sessions: (1) WAU, (2) MRR, (3) Customers, (4) Time-on-platform, (5) NPS. Team divided 2/2/1/1/1. Decision: 'we'll WAU because people picked it.'" **Good example:** "After sessions NSM debate resolution, recognize underlying issue: strategy. Convene strategy session exec sponsor. Three weeks later: strategy resolved (we productivity product teams 5-50, optimizing value delivered team). NSM follows: 'Weekly active teams publishing deliverable'. metric debate took min after strategy clear." **How catch it.** Length NSM debate. sessions NSM actual disagreement. · h2:Red Flag NSM lives slide deck, dashboards=**Symptom.** Exec slide says "Our NSM WAA". Team's weekly review shows revenue, MAU, conversion. NSM nowhere team's daily dashboard. **Why it's bad.** metric isn't visible isn't North Star. team optimizes what they see daily; NSM isn't dashboard, team optimize whatever is. slide-deck NSM decoration. **Bad example:** "Exec deck slide 'NSM WAA'. Team's dashboard: widgets, none showing WAA. PRDs reference revenue, WAA. Standups never mention WAA." **Good example:** "NSM appears in: Team's main dashboard (top widget, 13-week trend). Weekly status update (first line 'Highlights'). PRD Section (KRs tie NSM inputs). Quarterly review (headline number). New-hire onboarding (one first things new joiner learns). stakeholder cannot find current NSM clicks, NSM operational." **How catch it.** Try find current NSM number. clicks operational. · h2:Red Flag 10: Inputs movable=**Symptom.** One inputs "market size" "competitive pressure" "regulatory environment". **Why it's bad.** Inputs levers team pull. External factors levers they describe playing field, team's actions. Including them input tree gives team excuse ("the input got worse; couldn't move NSM"). **Bad example:** "Inputs MRR NSM: (1) New paid signups, (2) Churn rate, (3) ARPU, (4) Market growth rate, (5) Competitor pricing moves." **Good example:** "Inputs NSM: (1) New paid signups, (2) Churn rate, (3) ARPU. three team-movable. Market growth competitor pricing tracked 'Context' section quarterly review inputs they background conditions team doesn't control." **How catch it.** input, ask: "can team move within quarter?" no, it's condition, input. · h2:Red Flag 12: NSM target without baseline=**Symptom.** NSM target: "Reach 50,000 WAA Q4". current value. trajectory. **Why it's bad.** Without baseline, "50,000" meaningless. team currently (need 10x growth) 47k (need normal quarter)? target's ambition cannot evaluated; commitment cannot calibrated; missing target produces learning. **Bad example:** "NSM: WAA. Target: 50,000 Q4." **Good example:** "NSM: WAA. Current (May 2026): 12,400. Trajectory (last quarters): 8,200 9,400 10,800 12,400 (~14%/qtr growth). target: 22,000 (~75% lift, well above trajectory; requires step-change activation experiment paid channel expansion). Team confidence: 60%. miss 60% confidence, learn which assumption wrong." **How catch it.** Open NSM spec. current value present? trajectory shown? either, target unanchored.